Library of Congress.

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:37.830
And to thank you as well
for joining us today

00:00:37.830 --> 00:00:40.220
as we celebrate Human Rights Day.

00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:44.340 position:56%
Human Rights Day is officially
observed every year on December 10th

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:47.170
to commemorate the adoption
of the Universal Declaration

00:00:47.170 --> 00:00:50.360
of Human Rights by the General
Assembly of the United Nations

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:54.190
in Paris, on December 10th of 1948.

00:00:54.190 --> 00:00:56.660
The Declaration was designed
to provide a global framework

00:00:56.660 --> 00:01:01.860 position:56%
for human rights following World War
II and the end of the Colonial Era.

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:04.080
The Declaration can be
accurately characterized

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:07.130
as the first truly global
enunciation of human rights

00:01:07.130 --> 00:01:10.500
and is considered the
most translated document

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:12.060
in modern history.

00:01:12.060 --> 00:01:14.980
It's available in more
than 360 languages

00:01:14.980 --> 00:01:19.050
and new translations are
added on a regular basis.

00:01:19.050 --> 00:01:22.370
Given the status of the document,
its history and its impact

00:01:22.370 --> 00:01:25.500
on legal systems around the
world, I think it is very fitting

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:28.090
that my colleagues at the
Law Library of Congress,

00:01:28.090 --> 00:01:31.590
the world's largest law library,
and a leading research center

00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:33.020
for foreign comparative

00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:36.550
and international law are
hosting today's event.

00:01:36.550 --> 00:01:40.230
Today's program, the Impact of the
Miranda Warning on Human Rights

00:01:40.230 --> 00:01:43.920
in Eastern Europe will address how
American laws have affected human

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:47.970
rights developments in Romania
and the former Soviet Union.

