00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:46.410
of the U.S. Constitution giving
Congress the authority to legislate

00:06:46.410 --> 00:06:49.530
on the subject of the
bill to be introduced.

00:06:49.530 --> 00:06:52.220
So let me start off with what
I consider to be something

00:06:52.220 --> 00:06:55.970
like a constitutional authority
statement for U.S. advocacy

00:06:55.970 --> 00:06:58.300
on human rights in Europe.

00:06:58.300 --> 00:07:01.350
It comes from the organization
For Security and Cooperation

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:05.360
in Europe's 1991 Moscow Document.

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:10.310
And states that, quote, "The
participating states emphasize

00:07:10.310 --> 00:07:14.320
that issues relating to human
rights, fundamental freedoms,

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:19.700
democracy and the rule of law are
of international concern as respect

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:23.510
for these rights and freedoms
constitutes one of the foundations

00:07:23.510 --> 00:07:25.800
of the international order.

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:29.640
It categorially and
irrevocably declare

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:32.990
that the commitments undertaken in
the field of the human dimension

00:07:32.990 --> 00:07:37.690
of the CSCE are matters of
direct and legitimate concern

00:07:37.690 --> 00:07:39.710
to all participating states.

00:07:39.710 --> 00:07:41.490
And do not belong exclusively

00:07:41.490 --> 00:07:44.880
to the internal affairs
of the state concerned."

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:46.370
End quote.

00:07:46.370 --> 00:07:49.390
This unambiguous declaration
was reaffirmed

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:53.850
at the most recent
OSCE summit in 2010.

00:07:53.850 --> 00:07:57.060
And the commitments referenced
happen to be the richest body

00:07:57.060 --> 00:07:59.800
of human rights commitments
that bind all

00:07:59.800 --> 00:08:05.030
of the OSCE's 57 participating
states which of course includes all

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:08.620
of Europe, the countries
of the former Soviet Union

00:08:08.620 --> 00:08:11.450
as well as the United States.

00:08:11.450 --> 00:08:14.120
Obviously, there are many other
reasons for the United States

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:18.920
to care about rights that are
universal and inalienable.

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:21.610
But this is a pretty
good one to cite to those

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:23.830
who would dismiss our
concerns as meddling

00:08:23.830 --> 00:08:26.370
in others' internal affairs.

00:08:26.370 --> 00:08:29.130
In fact, during my time at
the U.S. Helsinki Commission,

00:08:29.130 --> 00:08:33.360
I used this declaration
as my email signature.

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:35.920
Now, I was asked to give the
American perspective and will do

00:08:35.920 --> 00:08:40.030
so today as a practitioner of
human rights policy in Congress.

00:08:40.030 --> 00:08:43.630
And as far as human rights in
general and human rights in Europe,

00:08:43.630 --> 00:08:47.580
Congress leads the United States
government in advocating for

00:08:47.580 --> 00:08:50.810
and legislating on
fundamental freedoms.

00:08:50.810 --> 00:08:54.910
As the branch of government
closest to American civil society

00:08:54.910 --> 00:08:59.560 position:56%
which cares a great deal about human
rights, Congress often sees merit

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:06.540 position:56%
in ideas and causes that bureaucrats
and experts may find inadvisable,

00:09:06.540 --> 00:09:10.220
unrealistic, or even impossible.

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:13.400
But it's precisely this
institutional tension

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:17.650 position:56%
that produced monumental human
rights legislation addressing abuses

00:09:17.650 --> 00:09:20.120
in Eastern Europe since Miranda.

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:24.320
These are the Jackson-Vanik
Amendment of 1974,

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:28.510
the creation of the U.S.
Helsinki Commission in 1976,

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:32.360
and the Magnitsky Act of 2012.

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:36.370
And most recently the Global
Magnitsky Act which is on its way

00:09:36.370 --> 00:09:38.720
to the President's
desk for signature

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:40.620
as we speak here this morning.

00:09:40.620 --> 00:09:44.100
I spent nearly a decade
covering human rights in Russia

00:09:44.100 --> 00:09:47.570
at the U.S. Helsinki
Commission which in the 1970s

00:09:47.570 --> 00:09:50.300
and '80s was the lead
U.S. agency for advocating

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:54.960 position:56%
for Soviet dissidents, Jewish
refuseniks, and the captive nations.

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:56.910
But during my time
on the commission,

00:09:56.910 --> 00:10:00.930
we focused on corruption
instead of communism.

00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:02.360
And while fighting corruption

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:05.800
and promoting human rights
is not the same thing,

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:10.250
there's enough overlap to at least
allow the casual use of one term

00:10:10.250 --> 00:10:13.060
to also include the other.

00:10:13.060 --> 00:10:17.170
In early 2009, I reluctantly
accepted a meeting

00:10:17.170 --> 00:10:20.900
that would dramatically change how
I viewed human rights advocacy.

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:23.840
Set a new precedent for how
the United States responded

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:26.330
to human rights violations
in Russia,

00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:28.720
and now offers a powerful
new mechanism

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:31.810
to address human rights
violations around the world.

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:35.420 position:56%
And one that happens to be
uniquely suited for this current era

00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:40.010
of shrinking budgets and
extreme transparency.

00:10:40.010 --> 00:10:42.280
This meeting was with Bill Browder,

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:45.890
who previously managed the best
performing hedge fund in the world

00:10:45.890 --> 00:10:48.760
and was for a time the largest
foreign portfolio investor

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:50.060
in Russia.

00:10:50.060 --> 00:10:53.470
I didn't know him personally, but
remembered him as being a champion

00:10:53.470 --> 00:10:56.990
of Vladimir Putin's
early economic reforms

00:10:56.990 --> 00:11:00.330
which made Browder's
expulsion from Russia in 2005,

00:11:00.330 --> 00:11:03.530 position:56%
all the more notable and perplexing.

00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:07.040
Bill came to tell the story of
his tax lawyer, Sergei Magnitsky,

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:09.460
who was in pretrial
detention in Moscow

00:11:09.460 --> 00:11:12.750
for having exposed the largest
tax fraud in Russian history.

00:11:12.750 --> 00:11:17.040
And was being subjected to
increasingly torturous conditions.

00:11:17.040 --> 00:11:20.080
Sergei's story was remarkable
in that it was a departure

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:24.310
from the usual tale of wealthy
Russian businessmen who had fallen

00:11:24.310 --> 00:11:26.800
out of favor with the Kremlin
and then were facing something

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:30.860
that might charitably be
called "selective justice."

00:11:30.860 --> 00:11:34.780
But Sergei was a young, middleclass
Muscovite who was not involved

00:11:34.780 --> 00:11:38.500
in politics, whose
client lost no money.

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:41.380
And was seeking only to
understand what we now know,

00:11:41.380 --> 00:11:44.250
thanks to Magnitsky's
heroic efforts,

00:11:44.250 --> 00:11:48.800
to be an elaborate scheme involving
senior officials, organized crime.

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:52.410
And the offshore zone to steal
at least a half a billion dollars

00:11:52.410 --> 00:11:55.940
from the Russian Treasury
and launder it abroad.

00:11:55.940 --> 00:11:59.050
This fateful meeting with Bill was
the beginning of efforts outside

00:11:59.050 --> 00:12:01.610
of Russia to save Sergei and later

00:12:01.610 --> 00:12:04.740
to honor his commitment
to the truth.

00:12:04.740 --> 00:12:07.260
Now it's easy to get jaded on
the human rights beat in Russia.

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:11.710
And work at the Helsinki Commission
in the Putin era was frustrating,

00:12:11.710 --> 00:12:15.090
low profile, and with
few visible successes.

00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:18.280
The North Caucuses simmered
with low intensity conflict,

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:22.820
creating a long list of victims of
forced disappearances and torture.

00:12:22.820 --> 00:12:25.140
Russia's free media
and civil society were

00:12:25.140 --> 00:12:26.440
under increasing pressure.

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:29.940
And the United States was
making a concerted effort

00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:33.400
to improve relations
despite these obstacles.

00:12:33.400 --> 00:12:37.200
I speak in the past tense because
I no longer work at the Commission,

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:39.620
but as we all know, the
Putin era continues,

00:12:39.620 --> 00:12:41.140
and the situation has worsened.

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:46.740
At the Commission, I saw my job
as scanning the horizon for cases

00:12:46.740 --> 00:12:49.360
where our attention might be
able to make a difference.

00:12:49.360 --> 00:12:51.850
And for cases that would be of
particular interest to our bi--

00:12:51.850 --> 00:12:55.830
our bipartisan Congressional
leadership.

00:12:55.830 --> 00:12:58.320
Not always an easy things to do.

00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:01.000
Whenever I learned of a case
that met these criteria,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.760
our usual approach was to try
and get a senior US official,

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:09.650 position:56%
preferably the Secretary of State or
even the President to raise the case

00:13:09.650 --> 00:13:12.260
with their Russian counterparts.

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:15.760
Frequently, we would only
learn if the case was raised

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:19.230
in the broadest possible terms,
and usually from a response

00:13:19.230 --> 00:13:22.680
from some lower ranking
official we didn't even write to.

00:13:22.680 --> 00:13:25.580
Thanking us for our
concerns, and assuring us

00:13:25.580 --> 00:13:28.100
that they share the same concerns.

00:13:28.100 --> 00:13:32.220 position:56%
Basically, the sort of mealy-mouthed
letter that makes you even angrier

00:13:32.220 --> 00:13:34.910
than had you been completely
ignored.

00:13:34.910 --> 00:13:37.310
And the Russian government
never paid any attention

00:13:37.310 --> 00:13:40.680
to these interventions,
nor did the press.

00:13:40.680 --> 00:13:45.350 position:56%
And then another journalist or human
rights activist would be killed,

00:13:45.350 --> 00:13:48.230
with little hope of ever
finding those responsible.

00:13:48.230 --> 00:13:51.710
And we dash off yet
another press release,

00:13:51.710 --> 00:13:54.370
condemning the latest
human rights outrage.

00:13:54.370 --> 00:13:58.380
It was all very unsatisfying,
but it was what we did

00:13:58.380 --> 00:14:00.350
because we had to do something.

00:14:00.350 --> 00:14:03.580
In an attempt to be fair
and spread our attention,

00:14:03.580 --> 00:14:06.210 position:56%
I had a few active files on my desk.

00:14:06.210 --> 00:14:08.400
And if I had been focusing
on one for a while,

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:10.730
I'd try to focus on another.

00:14:10.730 --> 00:14:13.520
And somehow the sense that
there were probably thousands

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:17.730 position:56%
of cases much worse than the ones
we were aware of was strangely given

00:14:17.730 --> 00:14:22.650 position:56%
as an excuse for not doing something
on the cases we did know about.

00:14:22.650 --> 00:14:25.210
In the summer of 2009,
human rights activist,

00:14:25.210 --> 00:14:28.780
Natalya Estemirova's
bullet-riddled body was found

00:14:28.780 --> 00:14:31.210
on a roadside in Ingushetia.

00:14:31.210 --> 00:14:34.440
She had visited our Washington
offices not long before her death.

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:40.290 position:56%
And it felt entirely inappropriate
to merely condemn her brutal murder.

00:14:40.290 --> 00:14:45.070
The time had come for action,
but again, what could we do?

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:48.650
At the Commission, Estemirova's
murder would be the last death

00:14:48.650 --> 00:14:51.020
of an activist where our
response would be limited

00:14:51.020 --> 00:14:55.390 position:56%
to the same old ineffective tools of
pleading for high-level US attention

00:14:55.390 --> 00:14:59.590
and calling for investigations
that are unworthy of the name.

00:14:59.590 --> 00:15:03.810
A few months later, on November
16th, 2009, Sergei Magnitsky,

00:15:03.810 --> 00:15:07.310
whose plight we learned about
earlier that year, was handcuffed

00:15:07.310 --> 00:15:10.270
to a bed in an isolation
cell and beaten

00:15:10.270 --> 00:15:12.830
by prison guards until he died.

00:15:12.830 --> 00:15:16.410
His torture and ultimately
murder was rigorously documented

00:15:16.410 --> 00:15:20.530
in his detailed and
voluminous legal complaints.

00:15:20.530 --> 00:15:21.830
And by the bureaucratic

00:15:21.830 --> 00:15:24.630
and authoritarian system
that killed him.

00:15:24.630 --> 00:15:29.030
Sergei was a young, idealistic
Muscovite who placed great hope

00:15:29.030 --> 00:15:31.850 position:56%
in then-President Medvedev's promise

00:15:31.850 --> 00:15:35.600
to end what Medvedev himself
had called "legal nihilism."

00:15:35.600 --> 00:15:38.740
Only to become its
most emblematic victim.

00:15:38.740 --> 00:15:42.690
At the Commission, we
began work immediately

00:15:42.690 --> 00:15:45.500
on assembling documentary
evidence of his false arrest,

00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:48.630
illegal detention,
torture, and murder,

00:15:48.630 --> 00:15:51.340
as well as on the massive tax
fraud against the Russian people

00:15:51.340 --> 00:15:53.850
that he gave his life to expose.

00:15:53.850 --> 00:15:56.510
We also combed federal
law for precedent

00:15:56.510 --> 00:16:00.830
on how we could address his
case in the United States,

00:16:00.830 --> 00:16:04.690
given that a cover-up was
gaining speed in Moscow.

00:16:04.690 --> 00:16:09.980
We found a Bush-era executive order
called Proclamation 7750 giving the

00:16:09.980 --> 00:16:13.900
President authority to bar foreign
persons engaged in corruption

00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:16.200
from entering the United States.

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:20.370
Losing a visa seemed a ridiculously
small strike at impunity.

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:23.510
And we weren't even sure if any
of those involved planned --

00:16:23.510 --> 00:16:26.400
visited or had planned
to visit our country.

00:16:26.400 --> 00:16:30.710
But in April 2010, Senator
Cardin, who was the Senate Chairman

00:16:30.710 --> 00:16:33.520
of the Helsinki Commission,
and now the ranking member

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:36.000
of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.680
decided to send an open letter to
Secretary Clinton, including a list

00:16:39.680 --> 00:16:44.850 position:56%
of 60 Russian officials complicit
in Sergei's false arrest, detention,

00:16:44.850 --> 00:16:50.160
torture, and death as well as those
involved in the crimes he exposed.

00:16:50.160 --> 00:16:53.710
And asked that she
use this authority

00:16:53.710 --> 00:16:56.580
to publicly ban their entry.

00:16:56.580 --> 00:16:59.840
Given our previous
experience of sending letters

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:03.640
into a non-responsive void,
we didn't expect much.

00:17:03.640 --> 00:17:06.560
But after releasing this
letter late on a Sunday night

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:10.370
as Moscow was waking up on
Monday, we awoke in Washington

00:17:10.370 --> 00:17:12.790
to fireworks in the Russian press.

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:15.670
Dramatic headlines
in the Western press,

00:17:15.670 --> 00:17:18.300
and Secretary Clinton
wanted to see the Senator.

00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:23.210
If we can gauge our
effectiveness by their reaction,

00:17:23.210 --> 00:17:25.620
this list was a direct hit.

00:17:25.620 --> 00:17:29.270
In fact, I think it was
Newsweek that ran the headline,

00:17:29.270 --> 00:17:33.240
"Cardin Drops Bomb on
Russia's Corrupt Elite."

00:17:33.240 --> 00:17:37.210 position:56%
And Russia's leading anti-corruption
activist, Alexei Navalny,

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:42.610
posted the list on his website
with a one-word headline: Wow.

00:17:42.610 --> 00:17:47.330
The [foreign language]
had become a rallying cry.

00:17:47.330 --> 00:17:50.280
We had finally discovered the
Achilles heel of corrupt officials

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:54.660
in Russia and around the world:
their exposure to the West.

00:17:54.660 --> 00:17:56.950
Having trashed the
rule of law at home,

00:17:56.950 --> 00:18:00.730
they stash ill-gotten gains abroad
in countries where due process

00:18:00.730 --> 00:18:04.690
that -- in countries with due
process that respect human rights.

00:18:04.690 --> 00:18:07.900
They also keep passports
with multi-entry visas handy

00:18:07.900 --> 00:18:11.480
in case they fall out of favor
and need to make a quick exit.

00:18:11.480 --> 00:18:13.940
Moreover, ours was an
asymmetric response

00:18:13.940 --> 00:18:16.560
that couldn't easily be countered.

00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:20.330
The Kremlin tried banning US
officials and freezing their assets

00:18:20.330 --> 00:18:24.150
and were met by jeers
from their own citizens.

00:18:24.150 --> 00:18:26.760
They also tried banning
US officials they viewed

00:18:26.760 --> 00:18:30.490
as having violated human
rights only to be drawn further

00:18:30.490 --> 00:18:33.030
into a public conversation
on the importance

00:18:33.030 --> 00:18:35.430
of protecting those rights.

00:18:35.430 --> 00:18:37.660
This new technology for
keeping human rights

00:18:37.660 --> 00:18:41.190
on the agenda was also
a fairer response.

00:18:41.190 --> 00:18:44.320
It shamed individual violators
without saying anything

00:18:44.320 --> 00:18:46.340
about their country as a whole

00:18:46.340 --> 00:18:49.550
or blocking any business
deals or trade.

00:18:49.550 --> 00:18:52.270
Further, it was an
approach that cost nothing

00:18:52.270 --> 00:18:56.890
and was easily replicable
in other countries quietly

00:18:56.890 --> 00:18:58.820
or with public debate.

00:18:58.820 --> 00:19:01.890
In fact, this week Estonia
became the first European country

00:19:01.890 --> 00:19:05.750
to pass a Magnitsky-styled law and
similar proposals are now pending

00:19:05.750 --> 00:19:08.280
in the United Kingdom and Canada.

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:09.920
In the coming months and years,

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:13.470
we fought an uphill battle spanning
two Congresses to take this idea

00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:17.210
that had the proverbial snowball's
chance into a new section

00:19:17.210 --> 00:19:18.940
of the United States code.

00:19:18.940 --> 00:19:21.640
Throughout the campaign,
our greatest support came

00:19:21.640 --> 00:19:24.450 position:56%
from Russia's besieged civil society

00:19:24.450 --> 00:19:26.800
and from the International
Human Rights community.

00:19:26.800 --> 00:19:30.260
While our greatest resistance
came from the Administration,

00:19:30.260 --> 00:19:34.190
the Kremlin, and the trade
lobby, in that order.

00:19:34.190 --> 00:19:38.390 position:56%
In fact, it was the Administration's
proxy blocking in Congress that led

00:19:38.390 --> 00:19:42.380
to the Magnitsky Act being tied to
Russia's Jackson-Vanik termination.

00:19:42.380 --> 00:19:46.610 position:56%
And it was the Administration's
desire to spare Russia that led them

00:19:46.610 --> 00:19:51.110
to propose that Congress make
the act explicitly global.

00:19:51.110 --> 00:19:54.220
They later reversed course and
joined the House leadership

00:19:54.220 --> 00:19:57.830
in insisting that it
be limited to Russia.

00:19:57.830 --> 00:20:01.030
The original Magnitsky Act also
set the stage for our response

00:20:01.030 --> 00:20:04.200
to Putin's unprovoked and
illegal war in Ukraine.

00:20:04.200 --> 00:20:05.660
With many of the early targets

00:20:05.660 --> 00:20:07.690
of the Magnitsky legislation
being added

00:20:07.690 --> 00:20:12.480
to Treasury's specially designated
nationals' list by executive order.

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:15.480
Should those sanctions ever
be removed prematurely,

00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:20.210
here or in Europe, I suspect
that the Magnitsky Act will stand

00:20:20.210 --> 00:20:22.280
as the most prominent rebuke

00:20:22.280 --> 00:20:25.230
to the violent kleptocracy
currently ruling Russia

00:20:25.230 --> 00:20:28.060
and menacing the entire region.

00:20:28.060 --> 00:20:32.540 position:56%
The new global Magnitsky Act builds
on the successes of the original act

00:20:32.540 --> 00:20:35.610
and they prove a valuable tool
for the new Administration

00:20:35.610 --> 00:20:41.090
to target human rights abusers
in China, in Iran, in Cuba,

00:20:41.090 --> 00:20:42.620
or anywhere in the world.

00:20:42.620 --> 00:20:45.980
I hope they implement it
vigorously and I'm confident

00:20:45.980 --> 00:20:47.800
that the Human Rights
community as well

00:20:47.800 --> 00:20:51.250
as Congress will be
encouraging them to do just that.

00:20:51.250 --> 00:20:53.010
Thank you.

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:54.500
&gt;&gt; Peter Roudik: Thank you, Kyle.

00:20:54.500 --> 00:20:55.800
Dr. Pomeranz.

00:20:55.800 --> 00:20:57.100
&gt;&gt; Dr. Pomeranz.

00:20:57.100 --> 00:20:58.400
Well, thank you very much, Peter.

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:01.980
It is always a pleasure to be at
the Library of Congress and to walk

00:21:01.980 --> 00:21:04.610
by the Law Library of Congress.

00:21:04.610 --> 00:21:07.850
A brief story: I did a
Ph.D. for five years,

00:21:07.850 --> 00:21:11.440
but I always like to say I have
five days I remember the most.

00:21:11.440 --> 00:21:15.160
And one of those five days
took place at the Law Library,

00:21:15.160 --> 00:21:19.880
and this may date myself, where I
was given a stack pass and allowed

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:24.680 position:56%
to go into the depths of the Library
of Congress, press some buttons

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:26.840
that I couldn't quite understand.

00:21:26.840 --> 00:21:30.450
But nevertheless, books began
to appear, and all of a sudden,

00:21:30.450 --> 00:21:33.870
there in front of me was
the largest collection

00:21:33.870 --> 00:21:36.860 position:56%
on the pre-revolutionary Advocatura,

00:21:36.860 --> 00:21:39.350
the legal profession,
in Czarist Russia.

00:21:39.350 --> 00:21:44.950
And I smiled because my Ph.D. had
gotten a huge lift that morning,

00:21:44.950 --> 00:21:47.540
and it was all thanks
to the Law Library.

00:21:47.540 --> 00:21:49.700
And I proceeded to spend a
good three months digging

00:21:49.700 --> 00:21:51.780
through what was available.

00:21:51.780 --> 00:21:55.740
And it was just a tremendous,
a tremendous opportunity.

00:21:55.740 --> 00:22:00.700
I'm going to follow on Kyle, but
take a little different approach

00:22:00.700 --> 00:22:02.600
to the discussion of Miranda.

00:22:02.600 --> 00:22:07.290 position:56%
Because as was mentioned at the
beginning, our, our goal is not only

00:22:07.290 --> 00:22:10.120
to look domestically but
also internationally.

00:22:10.120 --> 00:22:14.330
And looking at how US
law impacts foreign law

00:22:14.330 --> 00:22:16.670
and influences human rights.

00:22:16.670 --> 00:22:20.330
I'll focus primarily on Russia
but I'm also going to talk

00:22:20.330 --> 00:22:23.670
about other post-Soviet
countries as well.

00:22:23.670 --> 00:22:27.180 position:56%
And in the spirit of the Miranda
Warning, I'm actually going to delve

00:22:27.180 --> 00:22:31.320
into criminal procedure within the
Russian criminal justice system,

00:22:31.320 --> 00:22:33.720
but then expand to talk
about broader issues

00:22:33.720 --> 00:22:37.680
about how the United States
promotes legal reform abroad.

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:41.260
And at the very end, a general
discussion about the direction

00:22:41.260 --> 00:22:43.860
of Russia's legal trajectory.

00:22:43.860 --> 00:22:47.280
Now to do so, I want to issue
one caveat at the beginning.

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:50.430
I just finished reading
a fascinating

00:22:50.430 --> 00:22:53.620
and in many ways upsetting
book called Just Mercy,

00:22:53.620 --> 00:22:58.150
by the lawyer Brian Stevenson,
who details the problems

00:22:58.150 --> 00:23:01.470
of wrongly condemned people
in the US justice system.

00:23:01.470 --> 00:23:05.710
Suffice it to say, when you have a
chance to read about the underbelly

00:23:05.710 --> 00:23:10.300
of the US criminal justice system,
it has its fair share of problems

00:23:10.300 --> 00:23:13.650
and unpleasantness as well.

00:23:13.650 --> 00:23:16.340
So I want to emphasize that the
Miranda Warning is always the

00:23:16.340 --> 00:23:17.970
beginning of the process.

00:23:17.970 --> 00:23:21.450
It does not eliminate
necessary long-standing biases

00:23:21.450 --> 00:23:25.750
within a legal system that
can lead to unjust verdicts.

00:23:25.750 --> 00:23:28.790
And that is true of all legal
systems and not just to Russia.

00:23:28.790 --> 00:23:34.230
But as I mentioned, I'm going to
begin with criminal procedure,

00:23:34.230 --> 00:23:36.360
and I'm going to start
with the passage

00:23:36.360 --> 00:23:39.620
of the Russian Criminal
Procedure Code in 2001.

00:23:39.620 --> 00:23:44.120 position:56%
Now, I was doing the math, and I
realized that was just 15 years ago,

00:23:44.120 --> 00:23:49.800
but it really hearkens to another
era in Russian and Russian history.

00:23:49.800 --> 00:23:56.130
Because the Criminal Procedure Code
was signed by one Vladimir Putin.

00:23:56.130 --> 00:23:58.450
And at the time, it was
perceived in many ways

00:23:58.450 --> 00:24:01.200
as a very important liberal reform.

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:05.870
Transforming the Russian criminal
process and holding out the promise

00:24:05.870 --> 00:24:09.470
of reforming the corrupt
Soviet legal system

00:24:09.470 --> 00:24:11.830
that was still in place
inside Russia.

00:24:11.830 --> 00:24:18.650
Now, the 2001 Criminal Procedure
Code does possess a Miranda-style

00:24:18.650 --> 00:24:24.560
warning stating that when a suspect
is detained or is in custody,

00:24:24.560 --> 00:24:26.500
that that person has
the right to know

00:24:26.500 --> 00:24:29.200
of what he or she is suspected of.

00:24:29.200 --> 00:24:32.150
He or she has the right to
obtain documents related

00:24:32.150 --> 00:24:35.000
to the instigation
of the criminal case.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:38.350
And that person has a
right to avail themselves

00:24:38.350 --> 00:24:41.580
onto the advice of legal counsel.

00:24:41.580 --> 00:24:44.930
Yet 15 years afterwards,
few would argue

00:24:44.930 --> 00:24:49.250
that the Russian criminal justice
system has lived up to that warning

00:24:49.250 --> 00:24:51.610
or indeed to Western standards.

00:24:51.610 --> 00:24:54.620
And the question is why is this so?

00:24:54.620 --> 00:24:57.410
Or to ask the question another way,

00:24:57.410 --> 00:25:01.940
why has a Miranda-style
warning become superfluous

00:25:01.940 --> 00:25:04.380
within the Russian legal system?

00:25:04.380 --> 00:25:09.050 position:56%
And the answer can be found in a
fascinating statistic inside Russia,

00:25:09.050 --> 00:25:13.490
and that is the conviction rate of
Russian criminals who go to trial,

00:25:13.490 --> 00:25:16.420
and that statistic is 99%.

00:25:16.420 --> 00:25:21.980
Similar percentages exist in other
post-Soviet republics as well.

00:25:21.980 --> 00:25:24.820
And the question, when you look
at that, is how can that be?

00:25:24.820 --> 00:25:28.380
Why is, why is it that
99% of all people

00:25:28.380 --> 00:25:29.680
who go before the [inaudible],
face --

00:25:29.680 --> 00:25:35.070
inside the criminal justice
system end up being convicted?

00:25:35.070 --> 00:25:36.650
Now, on one hand you might think

00:25:36.650 --> 00:25:39.870
that maybe Russia has some
outstanding criminal investigators

00:25:39.870 --> 00:25:44.830
who are diligent and impartial and
always are able to get their man.

00:25:44.830 --> 00:25:47.020
But that really isn't the case.

00:25:47.020 --> 00:25:50.130
You also might think that it's
because of rampant corruption,

00:25:50.130 --> 00:25:54.980 position:56%
and in certain economic cases, there
are plenty examples of corruption.

00:25:54.980 --> 00:26:00.780 position:56%
But the average Russian criminal
defendant is male, poor, uneducated,

00:26:00.780 --> 00:26:03.820
and without any resources
necessarily to bribe a judge.

00:26:03.820 --> 00:26:07.290
So it's not really
corruption as well that,

00:26:07.290 --> 00:26:10.520
that explains the 99%
conviction rate.

00:26:10.520 --> 00:26:13.750
The major problem, as
I would put forward,

00:26:13.750 --> 00:26:16.710
and as Russian scholars
have themselves argued is

00:26:16.710 --> 00:26:19.960
that the incentives are all wrong.

00:26:19.960 --> 00:26:21.880
What do I mean by that?

00:26:21.880 --> 00:26:26.490
Because when you look at how
certain legal institutions

00:26:26.490 --> 00:26:31.210
and practitioners are
evaluated, they're evaluated based

00:26:31.210 --> 00:26:34.030
on convictions and acquittal rates.

00:26:34.030 --> 00:26:37.490
So for example, if I'm a prosecutor
in Russia, and I want to get

00:26:37.490 --> 00:26:40.900
on in the system, I will be judged

00:26:40.900 --> 00:26:46.710
by how many acquittals have
resulted in my prosecutions.

00:26:46.710 --> 00:26:50.510
So in other words, acquittals work
against me if I want to advance

00:26:50.510 --> 00:26:53.170
within the Russian
criminal bureaucracy.

00:26:53.170 --> 00:26:57.710
Similarly, if I'm a judge, I will
be evaluated by the percentage

00:26:57.710 --> 00:26:59.880
of cases that are overturned.

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:02.420
Again, most of the cases
that are overturned

00:27:02.420 --> 00:27:05.480
in the Russian criminal
justice system are acquittals.

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:10.290
So again, if I'm a part of the
legal, Russian legal bureaucracy,

00:27:10.290 --> 00:27:14.540
I have certain incentives
not to break the system.

00:27:14.540 --> 00:27:19.220
And that is really not to
somehow challenge this fact

00:27:19.220 --> 00:27:24.740
that Russia has a 99%
conviction rate.

00:27:24.740 --> 00:27:27.210
Now Russia has adopted
an adversarial system,

00:27:27.210 --> 00:27:30.880
at least a trial, where a defendant
is represented by a lawyer,

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:34.010
and the state is represented
by the prosecutor.

00:27:34.010 --> 00:27:36.800
But as I noted above, by
the time one gets to trial,

00:27:36.800 --> 00:27:39.020
the decision essentially
has been made.

00:27:39.020 --> 00:27:42.100
I once talked to a Russian defense
attorney and asked them, "Well,

00:27:42.100 --> 00:27:45.060
what do you tell your client
before you go to trial?"

00:27:45.060 --> 00:27:47.490
And he informed me he tells
them that they have a one

00:27:47.490 --> 00:27:50.390
in 100 chance of getting off.

00:27:50.390 --> 00:27:52.950
Again, you can imagine
that, you know,

00:27:52.950 --> 00:27:54.290
how that goes down with the client.

00:27:54.290 --> 00:27:56.620
But nevertheless, they, there
are people who are still willing

00:27:56.620 --> 00:27:58.660
to fight within the system.

00:27:58.660 --> 00:28:01.730
But if you are somehow going to get
the charges dropped against you,

00:28:01.730 --> 00:28:05.630
the crucial time to do it is
in the investigation process.

00:28:05.630 --> 00:28:07.500
And during the investigation
process,

00:28:07.500 --> 00:28:12.970
the Russian legal system primarily
retains the inquisitorial system

00:28:12.970 --> 00:28:16.450
that has so long prevailed
not only in the Soviet period,

00:28:16.450 --> 00:28:19.820
but even in the Czarist
period as well.

00:28:19.820 --> 00:28:24.800
And during, under an inquisitorial
system, it is the investigator

00:28:24.800 --> 00:28:26.560
that controls the investigation --

00:28:26.560 --> 00:28:29.440
investigation, and
the course of inquiry.

00:28:29.440 --> 00:28:33.050
And in many cases, the advocate or
the lawyer, the defense attorney,

00:28:33.050 --> 00:28:35.610
is appointed and paid by the state.

00:28:35.610 --> 00:28:37.510
And in order to keep
this steady stream

00:28:37.510 --> 00:28:42.010
of appointments going is
unwilling to challenge the state.

00:28:42.010 --> 00:28:45.500
Now, criminal procedure code
does allow defense attorneys

00:28:45.500 --> 00:28:47.500
to interview witnesses
and submit evidence

00:28:47.500 --> 00:28:51.500
into the case file during the
preliminary investigation.

00:28:51.500 --> 00:28:54.830
But that evidence is assumed
to be bias in many cases

00:28:54.830 --> 00:28:57.740
because it is submitted
by the defense attorney.

00:28:57.740 --> 00:29:01.650
Now you may ask, "Where is the
Russian judiciary in this process?"

00:29:01.650 --> 00:29:05.480
Which is the logical
check on potential abuse

00:29:05.480 --> 00:29:08.220
by investigators and prosecutors.

